    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>National Briefing | Rockies: Colorado: No Neglect Laws For Fetus</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Mindy Sink (NYT)</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Sink, Mindy</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Colorado Court of Appeals rules courts cannot use child-neglect laws to protect fetuses because state law does not apply to unborn children; human services dept seeked to intervene in case of mother who was using methamphetamines during her pregnancy (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The Court of Appeals has ruled that courts cannot use child-neglect laws to protect a fetus. The case began when a county human services department asked a court to intervene in the welfare of an unborn baby on the grounds that the mother was using methamphetamines. The state district judge would not do so on the grounds that state law applied just to dependent and neglected children younger than 18, not unborn children. The Court of Appeals agreed, stating that the law protects children only after birth. The baby in the case is living with his mother.</p>
        <p>Mindy Sink (NYT)</p>
      </block>
